<div class="left">
<h1>Precision</h1>
<div class="bodytext">
<p> Beyond the default pointer variations that come with the computer's operating system,
   applications with actions specific to them require unique pointers to signal these new functions the pointer can perform.
</p>
</br>
</br>
</br>
</br>
</br>
</br>
</br>
</br>
</br>
</br>
</br>
</br>
</br>
</br>
</br>
</br>
</br>
</br>
</br>
</br>
</br>
</br>
</br>
</br>
</br>
</br>
<p >Above are pictured some pointers that are unique to the Adobe applications each group is labeled with. The appearance of the
  pointer changes to match its new ability. This way, the user can be aware at all times of which tool they are employing.
  For the brush tool, you get a brush, for the magic wand tool, you get a wand. The design illustrates the function;
  making it also easier to remember what each tool is for. Since they have more tools, more complex apps such as photoshop
  have many more pointer variations than simpler ones like InDesign.

  The design of these pointers is clear, simple and thus easy to interpret, which makes them perfect for the interface they
  exist in. In professional softwares like these, the cursors have to be clear and useful while not being obstructive to the
   user's actions. They essentially have to be the last thing the user thinks about when working.
</div>
<div>
<p class="apps photoshop">Photoshop Cursors</p>
<p class="apps illustrator">Illustrator Cursors</p>
<p class="apps indesign">InDesign Cursors</p>
<p class="apps animate">Animate CC Cursors</p>
</div>
